I'm pretty sure we've met and exceeded that elusive goal of herd immunity we were lectured incessantly about, just months ago, by the science doers.  Now, crickets.

The herd immunity threshold is the percentage of the population that needs to be resistant to the virus to prevent spread.   The basic reproduction number, R0, is the average number of people who catch the disease from a single infected person when there is no immunity.  The rule of thumb is that the herd immunity threshold is 1-1/R0.   At the beginning of the pandemic, there were a lot of estimates of R0, but most of them were around 2.5.  That gives a herd immunity threshold of 0.6.  In other words, at least 60% of the population needed to be resistant to the virus to achieve herd immunity.   But recent, more-transmissible variants seem to have higher reproduction numbers.  If we assume that the reproduction number of the Omicron variant is 5, then the herd immunity threshold is 0.8.  It seems that vaccinating 80% of the population is not achievable.  That is why some experts have given up on achieving herd immunity.
